# Rules & Memory

Always  review .docs
Send cursor position only when user moves, but throttle updates to ~50–100ms to avoid flooding the network.
Always include userId, roomId, x, y, and a timestamp in the message.
On receive, update only UI state per user and never mix it with document or shared data state.
Remove cursors if a user has been inactive for more than ~5 seconds to keep UI clean.
Never render your own cursor locally—only render other users’ cursors as an overlay layer.
Use WebSocket only for small “operations/events” (like create/move/update), never send full app state on every change.
Keep a strict message format with type, roomId, userId, payload, and timestamp for everything.
Separate shared state (blocks, notes, data) from UI state (modals, hover, drag, local interactions).
Apply changes optimistically on the client first, then sync with server to keep UI fast and responsive.
Make everything room-based from the start and design for reconnection, deduplication, and out-of-order messages.